body:
I have a simulation which behaves differently with RTL than with the --protect-lib generated Verilated model and SV wrapper. 
This could be an issue in my testbench, but may also be a real issue in how the --protect-lib wrapper works. I am not yet sure, but wanted to discuss here for additional insight.

What I know is that if I replace all the blocking assignments in the generated wrapper's always block commented ...
`
// Select between combinatorial and sequential results
`
... with non-blocking assignments (so all outputs update in the same delta cycle) the issue is resolved. Clearly, this could easily be implemented as a patch as follows, but I am not sure whether or not this is the right thing to do in this case.

```cpp
--- a/src/V3ProtectLib.cpp
+++ b/src/V3ProtectLib.cpp
@@ -437,8 +437,8 @@ private:
         m_tmpDeclsp->addText(fl, " " + varp->name() + "_tmp__V;\n");
 
         m_nbAssignsp->addText(fl, varp->name() + "_seq__V <= " + varp->name() + "_tmp__V;\n");
-        m_seqAssignsp->addText(fl, varp->name() + " = " + varp->name() + "_seq__V;\n");
-        m_comboAssignsp->addText(fl, varp->name() + " = " + varp->name() + "_combo__V;\n");
+        m_seqAssignsp->addText(fl, varp->name() + " <= " + varp->name() + "_seq__V;\n");
+        m_comboAssignsp->addText(fl, varp->name() + " <= " + varp->name() + "_combo__V;\n");
         m_cComboParamsp->addText(fl, varp->dpiArgType(true, false) + "\n");
         m_cComboOutsp->addText(fl,
```

Let's consider a design where all outputs are synchronously updated using a single clock.

What happens if the TB is (rightly or wrongly) sensitive to an edge on one of these outputs, which triggers some action which has a dependency on all the other outputs?

With blocking assignments, I think the values that action will observe on these outputs will depend upon the order in which they appear in this generated sequence of blocking assignments (which I believe mirrors the declaration order on the original Verilated module)

With the RTL simulation however, all the outputs will be assigned in a single delta cycle (assuming they were assigned in a clocked always, using non-blocking assignments), and the observed state of any action triggered by one these outputs will be the previous value, for all other outputs.

I can try to put a test case together to demonstrate this.
